    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1958-11-04T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1958-11-04T06:00:00-05:00" n="137"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d137">
                <head>137. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in Yugoslavia</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d137fn0">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 768.5–<gloss target="#t_MSP1">MSP</gloss>/11–458.
                        Confidential.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Belgrade</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1958-11-04T12:00:00+01:00">November 4, 1958,
                        noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>471. Joint Embassy/<gloss target="#t_USOM1">USOM</gloss>/Agriculture message.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>We believe we should try get more mileage publicity out of our aid to
                        Yugoslavia. With special assistance for <gloss target="#t_FY1">FY</gloss>
                        1959 now settled, progress having been made on Development Loan Fund loan to
                        Yugoslavia, <pb facs="0398" n="366" xml:id="pg_366"/> and <gloss
                            target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss> 480 negotiations now under way, we feel we
                        have opportunity engage in publicity to our advantage.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>We accordingly believe would be desirable Washington issue press release
                        along lines suggested <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 472<note
                            n="1" xml:id="d137fn1">Telegram 472, November 4, outlined recent U.S.
                            economic aid to Yugoslavia. (<hi rend="italic">Ibid</hi>.)</note> which
                        would announce special assistance program for Yugoslavia for <gloss
                            target="#t_FY1">FY</gloss> 1959, indicate <gloss target="#t_DLF1"
                            >DLF</gloss> loan for Pancevo agreed in principle, and note <gloss
                            target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss> 480 negotiations are under way. If such press
                        release is to be issued, we suggest that prior to its issuance Department
                        could provide background briefing press pointing out relationship our
                        assistance to recent Russian actions, namely suspension Soviet credits,
                        including credit to Pancevo, and refusal thus far of Russians sell coking
                        coal to Yugoslavs. We would contemplate that after <gloss target="#t_DLF1"
                            >DLF</gloss> loan is finally settled and <gloss target="#t_PL1"
                            >PL</gloss> 480 negotiations completed, further press releases
                        announcing each of these developments would be issued.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Prior to issuance press release, we would propose show it to Yugoslavs as
                        matter of courtesy and for any reaction they may have. We expect that at
                        minimum Yugoslavs will not like such releases and at maximum will positively
                        object to it. It may be that after we have gotten their reaction, we may
                        wish reconsider and not issue such release.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>Advise.<note n="2" xml:id="d137fn2">In telegram 332, November 5, the
                            Department of State discouraged the proposed press release as “untimely”
                            in view of new Yugoslav Government complaints about the difficulties it
                            was encountering replacing cancelled Soviet credits with Western aid.
                                (<hi rend="italic">Ibid</hi>.)</note>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">O’Shaughnessy</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
